You can use render prop pattern here:

```js
// modal
  ...
  render() {
    const { children: renderProp } = this.props;

    return (
      &lt;div className=&quot;modal-body&quot;&gt;
        {renderProp(onClose)}
      &lt;/div&gt;
    );
  }
  ...

// using modal
// instead of
return (
  &lt;Modal&gt;
    &lt;ChildComponent /&gt;
  &lt;/Modal&gt;
);

// use

return (
  &lt;Modal&gt;
    {close =&gt; &lt;ChildComponent close={ close } /&gt;
  &lt;/Modal&gt;
);
```

Now `ChildComponent` has `close` props containing `onClose` handler.

P.S: By the way, it&#39;s better to avoid creating callbacks on each render, you can declare your `onClose` handler on class level instead of `render()` function:

```js
class ModalView extends Component {
  onClose = () =&gt; { ... }

  render() {
    // use this.onClose instead
  }
}
```

